author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Fix AppStream validation errors ("Equalizer")

Apparently appstream-glib (`appstream-util validate`) does not like
captions being less than 10 characters. Instead a short summary is used.

In the event of the screenshots being updated and/or exchanged for
screenshots that feature other areas of the app, one should consider
migrating to short 10-50 character summaries instead of a single word.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Add OARS 1.0 data to AppStream file

The "Open Age Ratings Service" free and commercial software to
inform users about data collection, and content that may be violent or
otherwise should be age restricted.

Basically it is just a way to tag content in so that users (and parents)
can be informed prior to installation and potential exposure.

While not that relevant to PulseEffects, given all values are set to
"none", it is still valuable to show this. That and it is now listed as
a submission requirement at Flathub.

Version 1.0 is used for now, in favor of 1.1 which only works with
GNOME Software >= 3.27.3. Other clients are unknown, while 1.0 is known
to be supported.

author: vmatare
message:
use 0 for negative normalized spectrum magnitudes

negative normalized magnitudes aren't supposed to occur, and setting
them to 0 looks more sensible than inverting them. By inverting them, we
blur out the detail in silent regions.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Use Gtk.FileChooserNative

Gtk.FileChooserNative will use a file chooser dialog that is native to
the desktop environment (when supported). It will also work in sandboxed
environments, such as Flatpak.

Mainly this solves the sandbox problem. Users should now be able to
import presets, no matter how they install the application.

Fixes #195

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Support non-standard python paths

Debian based distributions (any others?), deviate from the upstream
standard python paths. This results in the `pulseeffects` script failing
to find the main PulseEffects module.

Unfortunately the Meson module for python3 can only fetch upstream paths
like purelib.

This fixes that and should, in theory, simplify things for anyone that
might want to build a debian package.

Should fix #83

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Add script that adds new releases to appdata

This script automates the additions to release data in the AppStream
metainfo (appdata) file. It eliminates many possible human errors and
ensures the dates are consistent and always based upon the committed timezone.

The process of adding XML data is based on XML Style Sheets. This is
much safer and more reliable than simply using a tool like `sed`.

If the appdata already contains a release that matches the last tagged
version, no action will be taken.

Together all of this means it should be practically impossible for this
tool to accidentally overwrite any other data. Of course, it does
not hurt to first stage or commit any other changes.

author: jwatt
message:
Multiband Gate: Make clear Reduction is Max Reduction

The "Reduction" control sounds like it is used to apply a specified
fixed reduction. That is not correct. It actually acts as a limit
on how much reduction will be applied by the value of Ratio. This
rename will make in less likely for audio effects newbies (like
myself) to be frustrated and confused when trying to figure out how
this plugin works.

See the documentation for the non-multiband Gate at:
https://calf-studio-gear.org/doc/Gate.html

author: LebedevRI
message:
Gate: restore gating level bar

I have unintentionally dropped it in https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/pull/1627
I actually used to find it useful during configuration, so

While there, i've fixed the displayed level
to be actually normalized, not just inverted:
https://www.wolframalpha.com/input?i=1.0%E2%88%92%28x%E2%88%920.1%29%2F%281.0%E2%88%920.1%29+for+x+in+0.1+to+1.0
... where 0.1 is a substitute for the full gain reduction
and 1.0 is the gain of a fully open gate.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Add AppStream appdata xml

Upstream work on AppStream compliant application metadata and rename the
desktop entry file according to desktop entry specification.

The provided appdata has been validated against the strictest AppStream
compliance test. It passes when translations are provided. This means,
among other things, that software centers can display screenshots and a
high quality description.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Add unit tests for appdata and desktop file

These new tests will be run if in the meson test target. Tests are run
against files after localizations and other changes have been merged in.
That way if a translation contains something that is invalid it should
be caught as well (needs verification).

Practically tests can be run in two ways:

1. Run `meson _build`, change directory and then run `meson test`.

2. Run `meson _build`, then use `ninja -C _build -t test`.

These tests are "inspired" by the GNOME Builder meson setup. While easy
to implement, having randomly come across it did save me a lot of time.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Update pot and po files

Update all localizations against current template. Done by running:
ninja -C $builddir PulseEffects-update-po`

This is the equivalent to each translator updating their file against
the new template. Any strings that are already translated will
automatically be reused.

It is probably a good idea to to this at least prior to a release.

author: LebedevRI
message:
Multiband gate: fix annoying schema bug

The enum `com.github.wwmm.easyeffects.multibandgate.detection.enum`
is defined in this schema, but the enum `com.github.wwmm.easyeffects.gate.detection.enum`
is being used instead :) Thus, the schema is not hermetic,
and leads to really hard-to-diagnose bugs (if you don't know where to look)
when changing the plain gate scheme.

This took me way too long to understand...

author: vchernin
message:
tests: Fix flatpak updates workflow
Beforehand it would fail since it did not have the correct permissions, the normal GITHUB_TOKEN is not able to create forks, it can only operate within the repo.
Fix this by creating a new github user easyeffects-bot, getting a token with public repo access, and then ensuring we don't persist credentials.
The last one took me forever to figure out, despite the python f-e-d-c logs very clearly showing the correct URL and tokens were being used, in fact the normal repo token was being used.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Fix add-appdata-release utility

The initial script had a fundamental issue; the application version and
release dates were based on git tags. Since this script needs to be run
before a release is tagged, that tag will never include an up-to-date
appdata file.

Versions are now parsed from the main meson.build file. It works well
but there is one limitation, the order of the key/value pairs "version"
and "meson_version" matters. If the order of those keys changes this
script would also require adjustments.

Dates are now provided by the `date` command, using the UTC setting.
This offers consistency since it also is not affected by day light
savings.

An added benefit of these changes is that less external commands are
now used.

author: vmatare
message:
make the spectrum awesome

This commit adds settings that make the spectrum view much more useful.

Most importantly, its update frequency is now configurable from 1 to 200
Hz. Additionally, the magnitudes can now be scaled with an exponent:

final_mag = (scale * mag) ^ exponent

This way we can actually visualize what is happening. The defaults are
set so that the original behavior is unchanged, however the sweet spot
is at very different values:

Sampling Freq: 60 Hz (The usual screen refresh rate, no point in going
                      higher than that)
Scale: 1.2
Exponent: 3.0

With these settings, things actually become visible. Scale and exponent
are of course highly dependent on the type of audio material. For added
pleasure, also double the number of points and the height ;-)

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Add complete AppStream release data

Depending on at what time a release has been tagged the date of a
release will vary. This change bases dates by the author's local
timezone which is also the default behaviour of `git log`.

Dates can be gathered by using:

git log --tags --simplify-by-decoration --date=iso

Alternatively releases could be based on UTC, in which case some
release dates would have to be updated. This could be checked against:

env TZ=UTC git log --tags --simplify-by-decoration --date=iso-local

The 4.2.7 does not pass all AppStream validation tests, or rather not the
ones specific to appstream-glib. It is temporarily removed so that all
tests can be passed. If I could I would have rewritten it instead.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Improve support for buildtime options

Use standard build time options everywhere in favor of static values
like 'bin'. These options are now checked once in the main build file.

There is a limitation with the datadir build option. If used in
combination with the DESTDIR env var, the value of datadir will not
be respected. by the post install script. It simply can't because there
are no env vars exposed for the datadir option.

However most of the time 'share' (default) will be the datadir. So it
should not be an issue when the FHS directory structure is followed to
to some degree.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Fix issues with documentation

The recent introduction of debian build files also modified the
documentation in less than ideal ways.

This fix solves this by staying consistent with previous changes that
moved distribution specific instructions to the wiki. Specifically a
wiki page for community maintained distribution packages is introduced
and linked to.

Build instructions is removed altogether since it has long since had a
dedicated wiki page. Some instructions were incomplete anyhow or located
in the wrong section.

Showing incomplete build instructions at the top is bad, because it
decreases the likelihood of a user reading the complete wiki page, thus
missing information. This in turn leads to an increase in support issues.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Update appdata screenshots

It is good to note that screenshots should preferably be 16:9 according
to the AppStream specification.

Since PulseEffects windows are note 16:9 by default, it is a bit of a
hassle to meet this requirement. Currently the workaround used is using
`xdotool` to set a window size of "1244 700" for the main PulseEffects
window and a size of "886 521" for Calibration.

author: vchernin
message:
Add NEWS file along with script that tracks release information

When making a release run update-release-files.sh. Both the AppStream metainfo and changelog files will be updated with release notes.
For this to be useful, the NEWS file should contain correctly formatted release notes. For the next release, a template with correct formatting is added to NEWS each time a release is made.
After running update-release-files.sh, metainfo and changelog should not need to be modified directly to adjust release notes.

Important: this script is meant to be run at each release. If you do not, it might produce incorrect or confusing results.
Also, reusing old version numbers for new releases might cause problems.

Metainfo is used in GNOME Software and KDE Discover to show release info.
Changelog is a user-facing markdown file explictly mentioned in the readme.

Update/generate metainfo using appstreamcli news-to-metainfo.
Update/generate markdown changelog file using script that converts from the NEWS file.

NEWS is in util/ since formatted markdown is thought to be a more readable format. Also, there is no need to present both a CHANGELOG and NEWS file to users reading the README.

Reuses work from add-metainfo-release.sh originally from 04bd3e968f7e0ba79b9672882590affe445dc330

Release workflow:
1. Update version number in meson.build
2. Run update-release-files.sh script
3. Commit, tag and push to GitHub

boost/math/interpolators/cardinal_cubic_b_spline.hpp

was replaced by
boost::math::interpolators::cardinal_cubic_b_spline

author: AlexFolland
message:
minor equalizer.page English grammar fixes

"The user can choose between 1 and 32 bands" would actually mean that the user can choose only 1 or 32 bands, and nothing between them, despite using "between".  "The user can choose from 1 to 32 bands" is inclusive, meaning the user can choose any number of bands from 1 through 32.

When the noun is countable, "fewer" should be used instead of "less".

author: LebedevRI
message:
Gate: restore gating level bar

I have unintentionally dropped it in https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/pull/1627
I actually used to find it useful during configuration, so

While there, i've fixed the displayed level
to be actually normalized, not just inverted:
https://www.wolframalpha.com/input?i=1.0%E2%88%92%28x%E2%88%920.1%29%2F%281.0%E2%88%920.1%29+for+x+in+0.1+to+1.0
... where 0.1 is a substitute for the full gain reduction
and 1.0 is the gain of a fully open gate.

author: LebedevRI
message:
Autogain: fix display of `Internal output gain`

The `AutoGain::process()` is treating `internal_output_gain` as
a linear gain:
https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/blob/28d1172819424b16b8df4f274387cf6604ca95da/src/autogain.cpp#L322-L324
... yet the display code thought that it was in dB's:
https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/blob/28d1172819424b16b8df4f274387cf6604ca95da/src/autogain_ui.cpp#L96-L97

I don't know which of the two need to be adjusted, i fixed this one.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Update Flatpak install instructions

The LSP plugin collection uses a very restrictive license, that may not
even be considered open source (according to the OSI definition). On top
of this the recently added Expander plugin is currently proprietary.

In order to provide both the Expander and Delay plugins an extension
(com.github.wwmm.pulseeffects.plugin.lsp-plugins) has been added to
flathub. This solves the incompatibility with the GPL and makes it
optional if users don't want to install proprietary plugins.

The new extension is provided for x86_64 and i386. ARM is not supported,
because upstream does not provide any binaries.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Inform translators not to translate icon name

It seems to be a common issue with Gnome apps, that for some reason the
icon name string is made translatable.

This temporary solution seems to be widely accepted. It is not visible
in POEdit. Maybe it is in other editors, maybe not. At least it will
serve as a reminder during a pull request review.

DO NOT accept pull requests that fail to notice this.

author: LebedevRI
message:
`LSP Gate` implementation (Fixes #1596)

This ended up being rather boringly straight-forward
after figuring out https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/pull/1622.
I started by fully copying the `Compressor` effect,
which is also LSP-based, and is pretty modern,
and then changed things.

The `Sidechain`/`Sidechain Filters` tabs are exactly identical
as they are in the `Compressor`, and in general most of the code
is rather exactly identical to `Compressor`.
Seems like some common boilerplate could/should be extracted.

I'm sure i've missed something, but this is basically it.

Fixes https://github.com/wwmm/easyeffects/issues/1596

author: nekopsykose
message:
fix suffixed-+'s on regex's

these are not valid, and libc++ fails on these with:

libc++abi: terminating due to uncaught exception of type std::__1::regex_error: One of *?+{ was not preceded by a valid regular expression.

it happens to work on libstdc++, but the intention is the same without
the + and works with both

author: teneri66
message:
Emphasize that PulseEffects is equalizer

It might be not convenient for the ordinary user to find pulseeffects application from KDE/Gnome. I suggest we emphasize that PulseEffects is equalizer mostly. Eventually we will benefit once PulseEffects becomes a part of default set of applications installed with major distributions. Users will try to type in "equalizer" and will be able to find PulseEffects because "PulseEffects" is too technical (relates to pulseaudio), not everyone will know it / remember it.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Use XDG instead of hard coding

GLib provides a way to properly respect the XDG Base Directory
Specification.

It is true that the directory would almost always be the same.
However a user should be to change this by, for example setting
$XDG_CONFIG_HOME and the application should respect that change.

author: vmatare
message:
throw exception when a required plugin can't be found

This can happen if e.g. a user forgot to install required gstreamer
plugins or a package maintainer forgot to add dependencies.
If a required plugin is missing, pulseeffects is effectively broken and
should crash hard, so that e.g. package maintainers get notified and can
fix the package dependencies. The user should be clearly alerted that
something is missing and the installation is somehow botched.

author: vchernin
message:
Add Flatpak manifest
So you can clone and start building with gnome builder without dependency hunting.
Note `org.freedesktop.LinuxAudio.Plugins.LSP` and `org.freedesktop.LinuxAudio.Plugins.ZamPlugins` are not automatically installed, so plugins like the convolver do not work after building in gnome builder.
- Maybe there are ways of workarounding, see https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-builder/-/issues/1586
Manually copied 4 modules from flathub shared-modules/linux-audio to avoid a git submodule.

author: vchernin
message:
build: Cleanup speex dependency status
Speex was never actually used as a library, so there was no real need to declare it in meson.
Without the speex package installed, the code compiles and the speech processor seems to work just fine.
So only depend on speexdsp and everything still seems to work.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Fix appdata and desktop entry summary

The summary keys of these files fulfill the same function and in fact in
some situations the appdata key will be used in place of the dektop
entry key.

Using the same string is not just good for consistency. It also prevents
duplicate translation strings from being generated.

author: openglfreak
message: Correct latency number of DeepFilterNet effect.

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Properly initialize gettext

Without properly initializing gettext globally, translations will not
work in a prefix other than `/usr`. By properly initializing gettext
at an early stage translations will work irrespective of where the
localisation data is installed.

The gettext manual mentions that the recommended way of providing
"PACKAGE" and "LOCALEDIR" is via either the config.h file
or the Makefile. Neither is available, but Meson does provide the
standad `--libdir` option.

https://www.gnu.org/software/gettext/manual/html_node/Triggering.html#Triggering

By treating the pulseeffects launcher script as a configuration file it
is possible to use the values from the build system.

author: Vascom
message:
Fix build with GCC 10

This fix build error:
```
../include/plugin_base.hpp:10:25: error: expected ')' before 'tag'
   10 |   PluginBase(std::string tag, std::string plugin_name, const std::string& schema);
      |             ~           ^~~~
      |                         )
../include/plugin_base.hpp:17:8: error: 'string' in namespace 'std' does not name a type
   17 |   std::string log_tag, name;
      |        ^~~~~~
../include/plugin_base.hpp:7:1: note: 'std::string' is defined in header '<string>'; did you forget to '#include <string>'?
```

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Initial meson implementation

Add support for the meson build system and restructure how data files
is stored in the repository.

Meson has the advantage over setuptools that it will automatically
install all files to the correct locations for the respective operating
system or distribution. No more manual copying of files post build.

Supporting AppStream appdata, including translations is very complicated
without a native build system. By using Meson it is possible to
translate both the application, desktop entry, appdata and even the
gschema files, in a single PO file. This means a much simpler workflow
for translators.

The desktop entry file is renamed according to the freedesktop, desktop
entry specification, (using the "reverse DNS" convention). This is
required to support certain tags in AppStream appdata and remves the
need to rename it at build time (Flatpak).

author: ishitatsuyuki
message:
Acquire realtime priority on PipeWire

Due to a poorly documented behavior [1] in PipeWire, EasyEffects was
running under normal scheduling policy which lead to an excessive amount
of audio dropouts.

Fix this by requesting the realtime client config profile.

[1] https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/pipewire/pipewire/-/issues/2024

author: AsavarTzeth
message:
Remove appdata release descriptions

This data is currently impractical, and even less practical to translate.

Since PulseEffects does very rapid releases, there is little time to
write proper, easy to read, release descriptions.

Another related problem is translations. There is no window of time for
translators to localize this data. This data could be marked so that it
is not translatable, but some meson or xgettext issues seem to prevent
this from working.

If this data is wanted in the future, simply revert this commit.

Fixes: #322

message:
Add meson version check

If nothing else this documents what version of Meson is required to
build/install PulseEffects.

Unfortunately since version 0.40.0 brings the change that removes the
requirement to define a language in project() and that is the very same
place the meson version check happens Meson will still report:

"Not enough arguments to project(). Needs at least the project name and
one language"
